}

{
    "analysis": "The metric-based anomaly detection returned 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) groups in the incident window, but all were filtered out because global_p95 == global_p5 (constant-series artifact). Thus metric thresholding did not yield any reliable non-constant anomalies to use for fault identification. Per the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to narrow down candidate components and temporal range: compute global thresholds for trace features, filter to the incident window (2020-05-26 02:00–02:30 Asia/Shanghai), and look for traces with values breaching global P95 or falling below global P5 (or other obvious anomalies). Trace anomalies can indicate latency spikes, increased error rates, or drops in row_count that help localize the failing component when metrics are uninformative.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Run trace analysis: Load trace.csv. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global_p95 and global_p5 using the full series in trace.csv (do NOT pre-filter by time). Then filter trace rows to the incident window May 26, 2020 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 Asia/Shanghai inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within the window compute: count_window, count_high = number of points with value >= global_p95, count_low = number of points with value <= global_p5, earliest_high_timestamp (first ts where value>=global_p95 or null), earliest_low_timestamp (first ts where value<=global_p5 or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Return a compact table (up to top 20 rows) named trace_anomalies ordered by (count_high+count_low) desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count_window, count_high, count_low, earliest_high_timestamp, earliest_low_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. If no trace anomalies are found, return message = 'no trace anomalies found in window'. Keep output limited to these aggregates."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis produced meaningful non-constant candidates (20 groups). Several container-level traces show P95-duration breaches and row_count changes within the incident window. Notable observations: docker_007 trace.self.local.duration_p95 had many highs (count_high=12) with earliest_high at 2020-05-26 02:03:00+0800; several JDBC and local duration_p95 traces on docker_001..docker_004 show earliest_high around 02:11:00+0800; some row_count traces on docker_002 show earliest_high at 02:11:00+0800. Metric-level analysis was uninformative due to constant-series artifacts. Therefore we should focus on trace timing and call relationships to localize the root cause: find which trace anomaly occurs earliest, which container appears as downstream peer in call chains, and which trace groups have sustained/high-count P95 breaches. We are not yet certain of the root cause component, precise occurrence time, or reason, so further trace candidate inspection is required.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace candidate results (or recompute trace-level thresholds if needed), filter to groups with count_high>0. Return up to 20 rows sorted by earliest_high_timestamp ascending. For each row include these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count_window, count_high, earliest_high_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95. Additionally, parse the trace_name to extract a simple 'peer' field: if trace_name contains 'to_<component>' or 'from_<component>', set peer to that <component> (e.g., to_docker_007 → docker_007; from_os_022 → os_022); otherwise set peer='self'. Return the table named 'trace_earliest_highs' (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and broad trace preprocessing and anomaly scanning. Metrics were unhelpful due to constant-value series (global_p95 == global_p5) so no reliable metric-level faults were found. Trace analysis produced meaningful non-constant candidates. Earliest trace breach in the window is docker_004 → docker_005 at 2020-05-26 02:00+08, but the most persistent and severe trace anomaly is on docker_007 (trace.self.local.duration_p95) with count_high=12 and earliest_high at 2020-05-26 02:03+08 and a longest consecutive-high segment of 3 minutes starting at 02:20+08. According to the diagnosis rules, when metrics are inconclusive, trace-level sustained and early deviations are strong indicators; the root cause level is likely the container/pod level. However we need to confirm docker_007's role in call chains (whether it is downstream faulty service) and whether docker_007's trace anomalies are the earliest sustained fault. To localize the root cause component and exact occurrence time, we should focus on all traces where docker_007 is involved (as the reporting cmdb_id or as a peer in to_/from_ traces) and compute per-trace sustained-high segments and earliest-high timestamps to determine whether docker_007 exhibits the most significant and earliest sustained fault relative to other pods.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze trace groups related to docker_007 only. From trace.csv: select rows where cmdb_id == 'docker_007' OR trace_name contains 'to_docker_007' OR 'from_docker_007'. For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) group compute global_p95 and global_p5 using the full series (do NOT pre-filter by time). Then filter to the incident window May 26, 2020 02:00:00 to 02:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (inclusive) and for each group compute: count_window, count_high (value >= global_p95), earliest_high_timestamp (first ts where value>=global_p95 or null), list of high timestamps (limit to first 10), max_value_in_window, longest consecutive-high segment length in minutes and that segment's start timestamp. Return a compact table named 'docker_007_trace_summary' with up to 20 rows and these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, peer (parse to_/from_ as docker_007 or other peer; else 'self'), count_window, count_high, earliest_high_timestamp, longest_segment_len_minutes, longest_segment_start, high_timestamps_list (<=10), max_value_in_window, global_p95. If no groups have count_high>0, return message = 'no highs for docker_007 in window'. Keep output bounded to the requested aggregates."
}

Brief reasoning summary: metric KPIs were uninformative (constant-series artifacts). Trace analysis found sustained and early P95-duration anomalies on docker_007 (earliest sustained breach at 2020-05-26 02:03:00 Asia/Shanghai), with correlated JDBC/local trace delays and no local CPU/memory spikes — consistent with application threads waiting on DB connections. Therefore the most likely root cause is a pod-level issue on docker_007 caused by DB connection limit exhaustion.

